			<div id = "comment-806" class = "comment">
				<p>I saw this RN42 but I am not going to do extensive work using bluetooth like large amount of data transfer etc. Suppose I need to control 10 switches in different locations, for that if I need to use 10 RN42 devices that isn't feasible. I need to do it using a less costly bluetooth receiver (custom made?)</p>
			</div>
			<div id = "comment-807" class = "comment">
				<p>I don't think that this is a realistic scenario. For a chip to be certified Bluetooth, it has to support the whole communications stack, which is what drives the complexity and the cost up. Assuming you do find an inexpensive Bluetooth chip to do your biding, you'll then realize that these have fairly large power consumption and you'll have to start thinking about custom boards with 802.15.4/ZigBee modules.</p>
			</div>
